Runway Growth
































Gary Kovacs
Board Member



About Gary Kovacs
Gary has served as a managing director of AVG Technologies N.V.’s management board and as Chief Executive Officer of AVG since 2013. Prior to joining AVG, he served as Chief Executive Officer of Mozilla Corporation from 2010 to 2013. Prior to joining Mozilla, Gary held senior leadership roles as Senior Vice President of Markets, Solutions & Products at Sybase through to the acquisition by SAP, and as General Manager and Vice President of Mobile & Devices at Adobe. Previously, he led Zi Corporation, a company specializing in embedded software and services for mobile and consumer devices. Before founding Zi Corporation, Gary spent 10 years at IBM in leadership positions in product management, sales, marketing and operations within the global software division. He graduated from the University of Calgary with his Bachelor of Commerce and an MBA with distinction. Gary serves as a board member of ePhox Corporation, Sensory, Inc. and Make-a-Wish Foundation (Bay Area Chapter). He is also a member of the University of Calgary Management Advisory Council. 




MBA with distinction as well as a Bachelor of Commerce degree from the University of Calgary
Board member of ePhox Corporation, Sensory, Inc. + Make-a-Wish Foundation (Bay Area Chapter)
Member of the University of Calgary Management Advisory Council














AVG Technologies NV (AVG) Gary Kovacs on Q3 2015 Results - Earnings Call Transcript | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»AVG Technologies NV (AVG) Gary Kovacs on Q3 2015 Results - Earnings Call TranscriptNov. 4.15 | About: AVG Technologies (AVG) AVG Technologies NV (NYSE:AVG)
Q3 2015 Earnings Call
November 04, 2015 4:30 pm ET
Executives
Bonnie McBride - Vice President, Investor Relations
Gary Kovacs - Chief Executive Officer & Managing Director
John Little - Chief Financial Officer
Analysts
Melissa A. Gorham - Morgan Stanley & Co. LLC
Vahid Khorsand - BWS Financial, Inc.
Joe Maxa - Dougherty & Co. LLC
Fred T. Grieb - Nomura Securities International, Inc.
Michael Wonchoon Kim - Imperial Capital LLC
Operator
Good day and welcome to the Q3 2015 AVG Technologies Earnings Conference Call. As a reminder, ladies and gentlemen, today's call is being recorded. At this time, I'd like to turn the conference over to Ms. Bonnie McBride. Please go ahead.
Bonnie McBride - Vice President, Investor Relations
Thank you, and thank you all for joining us today for AVG's third quarter 2015 financial results conference call. Joining me today from management are Gary Kovacs, AVG's Chief Executive Officer, and John Little, the company's Chief Financial Officer. Before we begin, I would like to remind you that this call is being webcast and recorded. A replay of both will be made available shortly after the conclusion of this call.
On today's call, we will provide you with details about our performance in the third quarter of 2015. Some of our comments may include forward-looking statements such as statements regarding our outlook for 2015. These forward-looking statements are based on certain assumptions and are subject to a number of risks and uncertainties. Actual results may differ materially. Please refer to the section entitled Forward-Looking Statements in our earnings release and read the Risk Factors in our filings with the SEC, including our 20-F filed on April 10, 2015.
I would also like to note that the results reported today include certain non-GAAP financial measures and that the numbers discussed on this call will be non-GAAP unless stated (1:21). We provide non-GAAP financial measures because we believe that they are the most valuable way to review our core operating results. We have provided a reconciliation of non-GAAP measures to their comparable GAAP measures in our earnings release, which is available on our website and which has also been filed with the SEC.
The forward-looking statements and risks stated on this conference call are based on current expectations as of today and AVG assumes no obligation to update or revise them, whether as a result of new developments or otherwise.
I will now turn the call over to Gary Kovacs.
Gary Kovacs - Chief Executive Officer & Managing Director
Thank you, Bonnie, and good afternoon, everyone. First of all, thank you for joining us today as we report our Q3 quarterly results. And on today's call, as is typical, I will provide an overview of the quarter and a particular focus on the strategic accomplishments behind the results. I will then turn the call over to John Little, our Chief Financial Officer, who will provide a detailed review of the financials. And, of course, we will then open the call up for questions.
So let me start today by saying that I am very pleased with the progress we are making in the transition we started two years ago, which is towards our vision of becoming the online security company, offering integrated and easy-to-use security services anywhere any of us go online. This transition has also enabled us to develop a much more predictable and sustainable financial model, as evidenced by the results we are reporting today.
In the third quarter, we delivered solid year-over-year revenue growth of 17%, despite facing much stiffer FX headwinds than we've seen so far this year. Growth continues to be driven by strength in subscription revenue, which grew 28% over the same period last year, and which continues to comprise the vast majority of total revenue. Along with this, we generated cash conversion of 25% for the quarter.

To achieve our vision, our strategy has been simple; optimize and expand our core consumer business, building on the great foundation we have established over the years, while thoughtfully investing in the growing segments of mobile and small and medium business.
Now let me share a few of the highlights in each of our business segments with you today. First, in our consumer segment, we continue to add products and services and over the past two years have evolved from two products on one platform to four product families across multiple platforms. This expansion has helped us meet the growing consumer demand for security across all devices, as well as execute on our goal to diversify and broaden our offerings in order to mitigate dependence on any single product.
Today, our consumer segment includes products in each of the categories of privacy, protection and performance. These include our core products like AV or antivirus and TuneUp, as well as Privax, our privacy solution through the acquisition of the same company, and mobile services such as those provided from Location Labs, as well as our growing category of alternative monetization technologies including search and advertising. And all of these are being integrated under the AVG Zen initiatives that I will talk more about.
So let me go into more detail on each of these. The core of our consumer business are desktop antivirus and TuneUp products continues to perform very well. This quarter we grew desktop revenue 4% against what many of you'd know is a very challenging market, and simply, I think the team did a fantastic job this quarter. Along with this, adoption of AVG Zen-enabled products is progressing with strong results.
We ended the third quarter with 17 million total Zen users, up over 50% from 11 million last quarter. This was driven by our move from the control-testing phase of the rollout of Zen-enabled products to a much more comprehensive, systematic deployment, which included rollout to multiple new geographies, as well as broader availability and distribution, including a larger base of free users.
With this broader rollout, I'm very encouraged that the key statistics around AVG Zen continue to be strong. Specifically, the registration rate for Zen-enabled PC products remains substantially higher than the 3% for non-Zen enabled products. And the ratio of applications per device continues to rise and is now at 1.37 applications per device compared for 1.08 for non-Zen enabled mobile products.
This is very significant, because the deployment to free users typically would reduce conversion substantially, which tells us that the core benefit of Zen to simplify the adoption of a broader set of security, privacy and identity solutions for users around the world, appears to be valued by our users.
As the expanded rollout continues, we will implement additional monetization schemes that we will test along with, of course, the continuation of our base monetization strategy. And in this, we expect to turn on the full subscription engine in the first half of 2016.
Also in our consumer business, our recent acquisition of Privax, a leading provider of digital privacy services to consumers, including the award-winning VPN service, is progressing well and in line with our optimistic expectations. This quarter alone, we saw nearly 50% growth in users signing up for recurring billing plans.
Turning to platform, both sides of this business, the organic and inorganic side, continued as expected. Starting with the inorganic search business, we continued to successfully wind this down, consistent with the plan that we announced when we exited the business nearly two years ago.
On the organic search business, this remained steady and performed to our expectations. However, I must comment that the search market itself continues to be quite dynamic. Over the last several years, we've managed, through various significant changes, including browser policy and technology changes, terms of service changes, and operating platform changes. And this year is no exception. In fact, the pace of change in this industry seems to have increased. Most recently, major browser providers have developed new strategies to protect their default search offerings, which typically means that users must take even more actions if they want to change their search provider. Now given the complexity and time required to this, less users actually make it all the way through the flow, which of course, affects our conversion rate.

The rollout of the new Windows 10 operating system is also accelerating, which introduces even more restrictions for search placements on that platform. The combination of these factors has undoubtedly increased the volatility in this market, creating uncertainty in our revenue expectations for search going forward. The good news is, given the solid performance in our other areas of growth and our more diversified revenue base now, we believe we can mitigate the impact on some of these changes we will likely face going forward. John and I will talk more about this later on in the call.
Turning now to our investment areas and starting with mobile, I'm very pleased to report that we saw increases in both our carrier-based distribution revenue as well as our emerging investment areas, including mobile advertising and direct-to-consumer licensing. Total mobile revenue for the quarter was $17.4 million, resulting in revenue in the first nine months of the year of $46.8 million. This validates our previous guidance that mobile is expected to be a $60 million to $70 million business in 2015. Within this, Location Labs is performing very well and in line with our expectation. The core rollouts that we had scheduled are progressing on plan, and we're beginning to develop and deploy new products into this channel also.
Last week, at Futurecom in Brazil, we introduced the first collaborative product between AVG and Location Labs, which is the AVG Family Graph. Now put very shortly, AVG Family Graph enables users to connect and communicate with family members using their location app, while also creating an ongoing family social graph, which really provides a view into intra-family connections.
While providing great benefit to users, it also helps operators attract and retain valuable family plan subscribers, which have been successful in the U.S. and are now a high priority for carriers in the international market. I'm encouraged by the initial feedback of this launch and look forward to reporting more as these products and others develop into the future.
Also in mobile, we continue to work on and develop new go-to-market partnerships for our mobile products. We currently have partnerships in place with Sony, TCL, and ZTE. And as they all continue to come on line and deliver more handsets, we are seeing increased adoption of our products and now have nearly 16 million active users from these partnerships, which is up from 14 million since our last earnings.
Like you, we've been watching the turmoil in the handset market as the device manufacturers compete for position in the global market. And because of this, we don't believe we have yet fully benefited from these relationships, but given the progress we have made as well as the new partnerships that we are developing and will announce, we are well positioned to take advantage of the opportunity as the market settles and matures.
Turning to SMB, we delivered 13% top-line growth over last year, as we continued to invest in this important segment. As we discussed in the last earnings call, our expectation of the uptake of our cloud-based services was not where we wanted it to be as a result of our existing customers' commitment to our traditional on-premise product.
To fix this, we have taken specific actions to improve our go-to market strategy, including a significant restructuring and streamlining of the business and further simplification of our products to make it even easier for our resellers to go out with our products to serve their end customers' needs. This restructuring and leadership changes, we believe, will put us in the right position to capitalize on a large and growing opportunity.
We believe strongly in this market and we'll continue to invest as we have been in anticipation of accelerated growth in the future. To do this, we have also continued to deliver best-in-class products. And during the quarter, we launched AVG Business Managed Workplace Version 9.2. This latest version contains multiple enhancements and is a fully-integrated remote management and monitoring platform that is winning quite a lot of critical acclaim. It is developed based on an award-winning technology and should augment our improved go-to market strategy to really enhance our cloud offering.

So that's a brief summary of the core consumer business as well as our investments in mobile and SMB. All of this has allowed us to increase our paid user count, which was a core focus we started last quarter. Today, we are very pleased to announce that we have surpassed 20 million paid users, which is a major milestone indicating that we are actually executing quite well on our monetization strategies.
Total users remain steady to slightly up at just over 200 million for the quarter, which is in line with my previous comments on our heightened focus on paid users, as well as reflection of the current dynamics affecting our mobile channel distribution partners. Going forward, we believe that the more accurate measure of our success will be paid user growth as well as total mobile user growth.
Finally, while we can talk about all the great things that we've done, it is always nice to get external recognition and we are pleased that we've received some awards over the (13:53) something we all take great pride in.
First of all, AVG scored 100% with AV-TEST as we achieved 1,005 detection rate of real world malware and a 100% detection of widespread malware. Second, AV-Comparatives Malware Removal report awarded AVG with the highest award mark of Advanced+.
Now, in recognition of a lot of this plus so much more, AVG remained rank number six globally and the top European company on the Cybersecurity 500 list. As you will recall, investments in the quality and value of our products has been a core focus for us over the last two years, and I'm very proud of the entire team for their contributions to make this happen.
Before turning the call over to John, I want to stress that the growth and diversification we have realized over the past few years has been achieved with roughly the same capital structure as we had when we went public 3.5 years ago.
We are committed to continuing this efficient stewardship of our capital, and in keeping with this, we are announcing today a new share repurchase program of up to $40 million. The program will become effective when our trading window opens next Monday, and our goal is to complete about 75% of this over the next three quarters.
With that, let me now turn the call over John Little to review the financials in more detail. John?
John Little - Chief Financial Officer
Hello, everybody. In Q3, we delivered total revenue of $108.2 million and earnings per share of $0.42. Our subscription business contributed $87.8 million of revenue, while our platform business contributed $20.4 million. Subscription revenue grew 28%, driving total revenue growth to 17% over the same period last year. And we're pleased to report that the share of sustainable, predictable subscription revenue has increased again to 81% of total revenue compared to 74% a year ago. Platform revenue showed a contraction of 14% over the same period last year, which was entirely driven by our continued exit from the third-party distribution business.
Adjusting for a negative foreign exchange impact of approximately $2.9 million, total revenue for the quarter would have amounted to $111.1 million. Year-to-date, we have now seen an estimated negative impact on our revenue from foreign exchange of $7.2 million and on booking of $15.7 million. Bookings for the quarter were $106.7 million compared $85.9 million over the same period last year.
From a segment perspective, the consumer business contributed $91.6 million in the third quarter of 2015 compared to $77.7 million over the same period last year, representing 18% growth. Driving this number was an increase in consumer subscription revenue, which reached $71.2 million compared to $54 million in Q3 2014, an increase of 32%.
Consumer desktop revenue reached $55.1 million in the quarter, showing an increase of 4% over the same period last year, with an improvement in renewal rate, largely driven by auto billing acceptance; auto billing being a default feature in our new product.

Total mobile revenue was $17.4 million in the quarter, up from $1.7 million over the same period last year, driven primarily by continued growth in carrier-based distribution. Of this revenue, $16.1 million was subscription revenue with the remainder being platform revenue from mobile advertising.
And finally, within the consumer segment, our platform revenue is $20.4 million; $19.1 million of search with the balance being primarily mobile advertising. Searches were approximately 650 million compared to 740 million in Q3 2014. Third party search revenue accounted for $1.9 million compared with $5.6 million a year ago.
Turning to SMB; this segment contributed $16.6 million in revenue in the third quarter, compared with $14.7 million last year. This increase of 13% in SMB revenue was driven primarily by the Norman acquisition. During the third quarter 2015, SMB annualized monthly recurring revenue reached $22 million compared to approximately $19 million a year ago. Combined AMRR for the quarter, including Location Labs, Privax and SMB reached $94 million, up from $87 million in the previous quarter.
Now, SMB has made significant progress over the last 12 months, but as Gary said, we did not feel it was progressing at the rate we expected. Accordingly, we have undertaken a restructuring of the segment to ensure we are both more focused on our strategic objectives to drive monthly subscription revenues, and to reach breakeven status, which we have targeted to be Q4 2015.
We are taking a number of actions to realize this, including releasing approximately 35 employees, outsourcing in proportion of our helpdesk, as well as restructuring the management of the division. We estimate that this will save us around $3 million over the next 12 months, and we intend to apply these savings and focus spending to continue to drive this business. We remain confident in the business opportunity in front of SMB and believe that these actions will allow us to attain our growth objectives more quickly.
Turning to user detail, total active users at quarter end were 202 million compared with 188 million a year ago. Mobile users reached 108 million, showing an increase of 18 million or 20% year-over-year, as our partnerships with mobile manufacturers and carriers gain traction. Sequentially, total user count remained flat as growth in the mobile user count was offset reductions in free desktop users.
During the quarter, the paid user count reached the milestone of 20 million compared to 14 million a year ago, again, driven by growth in mobile user count. While paid desktop users remain flat, we continue to drive value from them with paid consumer desktop ARPU rising to $6.72 compared to $6.10 in the third quarter last year, an increase of over 10%.
Turning to margins and profitability; gross profit margin was 87% compared to 91% last year, mainly due to additional infrastructure to support the increasing scale of the business, and acquisition accounting impacts of our recently acquired companies.
Operating income for the third quarter was $29.5 million, and operating margin was 27%. This compares with $34.8 million and 38% year-over-year. The decrease in operating margin was primarily due to the impact of acquisition and additional compliance-driven expenditures, although we did spend additional from the marketing during the quarter, as we continued the evolution of our business model. Operating margin year-to-date remained strong at 29%.
Interest and other expense in the quarter was $4.1 million compared to $1.2 million a year ago. Net income was $22.2 million in the quarter compared to $29.4 million during the same period last year, yielding diluted earnings per share of $0.42 when taking into consideration 53.3 million weighted average shares outstanding.

Excluding $3.8 million in expenses related to enhancing the company's internal financial controls and procedures, net income would have been $26 million or $0.49 per diluted share. These expenses, which are expected to decrease substantially by the first quarter of 2016, were driven by the significant investments being taken to implement new internal controls and systems that are commensurate with the scale and complexity of our current business.
Turning to cash flow, free cash flow was $27.4 million and cash conversion 25% in the quarter, compared with $16.4 million and 18% year-over-year. Cash conversion year-to-date stands at 19%. After an intensive year of M&A activity and backed by the strong cash flow of the business, we would like to announce, as planned, the initiation of a new anti-dilutive share repurchase program. This will be for approximately $40 million in total, of which we expect to execute around $30 million over the next few quarters. Further detail will be announced externally in forthcoming days.
Looking to the balance sheet, cash and cash equivalents were $144.5 million as of September 30, 2015 compared with $117.2 million at the end of the previous quarter and $44 million at the end of Q3 2014. Due to strong cash generation, the net debt position was reduced from $107 million at the end of the second quarter to $79.2 million at the end of the third quarter.
In the fourth quarter, we will be paying another installment of the performance based Location Labs earn-out of approximately $25 million. Deferred revenue at September 30, 2015 was $196.7 million compared to $188.7 million over the same period last year.
Turning to our outlook for 2015, based on the information currently available, we are narrowing our previously stated expectations of full year 2015 revenue to be in the range of $426 million to $430 million. Net income is expected to be approximately $95 million or roughly $1.80 per diluted ordinary share based on approximately 53 million shares outstanding. Operating margins are expected to be 30%.
As you've heard, I've decided to leave AVG and I'll be staying with the company to ensure a smooth transition to my successor. I'd like to provide – I'd like to take this opportunity to provide a brief summary of how we've transformed our business in the 3.5 years since the IPO, something of which I'm very proud.
In Q1 2012, we had $46.5 million in subscription revenue and two basic products, various versions of PC security for consumer SMBs and PC TuneUp.
As of this quarter, we have subscription revenue of $87.8 million, an increase of 88%. And as Gary said, we've also added additional product families. We've developed AVG Zen to deliver cross platform services, built two SMB SaaS products, CloudCare and Managed Workplace, and acquired two mobile products in location and control. Most recently, we acquired Privax, which gives us a VPN privacy offering.
Now, the nearly $88 million of subscription-based revenue in this quarter, roughly $55 million is highly predictable, based on renewals and monthly SaaS subscriptions. And this $65 million in recurring revenue is more than we had in total subscription revenue when we went public.
Further, we've diversified into new strategic areas and today over 30% of this recurring revenue is mobile and SaaS, which we have grown in the last three years from zero. I think if you look around Silicon Valley, this would constitute a very large mobile and SaaS security business with 50% growth last year and growing at 30% heading into next year. And we've done this (27:08) roughly the same share count and the same net debt as when we went public. And I believe from here, our strategic opportunities continue to broaden and deepen. And now back to Gary for closing remarks.

Gary Kovacs - Chief Executive Officer & Managing Director
